# expected: S01
# `event.period_id` is marked `foreign_key` and a relationship joins it to
# the `primary_key` column `period.id` — but only by a *range* conjunct.
# A range predicate relates two columns without referencing one from the
# other, so it cannot resolve a foreign key: S01 must still fire.
# (Cardinality is many-to-one with `period.id` as the "one" side, so S06
# stays quiet and the diagnostic isolates S01.)

$version: "0.1.0"

tables:
  - name: event
    columns:
      - name: id
        type: number(id)
        constraints: [primary_key]
        examples: [1, 2]
      - name: period_id
        type: number(id)
        constraints: [foreign_key]
        examples: [1, 2]

  - name: period
    columns:
      - name: id
        type: number(id)
        constraints: [primary_key]
        examples: [1, 2]

relationships:
  - join: event.period_id >= period.id
    cardinality: many-to-one
────────────────────────────────────────
error: [S01] Every `foreign_key` column must have a matching relationship to a `primary_key`.
  --> spec/s01-fk-range-conjunct-only.yaml:20:21
   |
12 |   - name: event
...
18 |       - name: period_id
19 |         type: number(id)
20 |         constraints: [foreign_key]
   |                     ^^^^^^^^^^^ is `foreign_key` but no relationship points it at a `primary_key`
